## Deploying new images

One command from the repo root:

    ./deploy                    # nginx image (rebuilds Reminders frontend)
    ./deploy rust               # backend image
    ./deploy nginx rust backup  # any combination

It builds and pushes the images to gcr.io/crypto-isotope-229419, pulls and
restarts on the VM, purges the Cloudflare cache, and verifies the live
bundle and API; it exits non-zero on any failure so it can run unattended.
Needs docker group access, the gcloud SSH key in an ssh-agent, and
~/.secrets/cf-api-token. TileRender wasm must be rebuilt separately
(TileRender build scripts) if it changed - the nginx image bakes in
TileRender/www/dist as-is.

Manual fallback: on the VM the old docker-credential-gcloud helper is
broken; log in with the metadata-server token instead (service account has
devstorage.read_only):

    TOKEN=$(curl -s -H 'Metadata-Flavor: Google' \
      'http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/service-accounts/default/token' \
      | python3 -c 'import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin)["access_token"])')
    echo "$TOKEN" | sudo docker login -u oauth2accesstoken --password-stdin gcr.io

Then: sudo docker-compose pull && sudo docker-compose up -d

IMPORTANT: Cloudflare has a cache-everything rule - purge the cache after
deploying frontend changes, or stale HTML keeps referencing deleted hashed
assets. Either in the dashboard, or via the API (token in
~/.secrets/cf-api-token on the dev machine has Cache Purge permission):

    curl -s -X POST \
      "https://api.cloudflare.com/client/v4/zones/492aee868243cb67393d7b638ffac598/purge_cache" \
      -H "Authorization: Bearer $(cat ~/.secrets/cf-api-token)" \
      -H "Content-Type: application/json" --data '{"purge_everything":true}'

## Postgres

postgres:17-alpine on volume thjread_db-data-pg17 (trust auth inside the
compose network). Migrated from postgres 12 on 2026-07-04 by restoring
s3://reminders-backup/pre-pg17-migration into a fresh volume. The old pg12
volume thjread_db-data is kept as a rollback; delete it once confident:
    sudo docker volume rm thjread_db-data

Backups: hourly/daily/weekly pg_dump to s3://reminders-backup (versioned
bucket; lifecycle keeps hourly versions 1 day, daily 14 days, weekly 365 days).
Restore drill: aws s3 cp s3://reminders-backup/daily - | \
    sudo docker exec -i thjread_db_1 psql -q -U postgres -d postgres
(into a fresh volume; the dump includes schema.)

